form of encapsulation for a behavior-only type. All state flows through method parameters. This mirrors the Claude Code agent exactly and is the correct design -- agents are lightweight factories for behavior, not state containers.\\n\\n- **Invariant Expression**: 7/10\\n  The compile-time interface checks (`var _ agent.HookSupport = (*CopilotCLIAgent)(nil)` and `var _ agent.TranscriptAnalyzer = (*CopilotCLIAgent)(nil)`) are good. However, the `HookSupport` check is in `lifecycle.go` while the `TranscriptAnalyzer` check is in `transcript.go`. Claude Code follows the same pattern, so this is consistent but slightly scattered. The interface contract is clearly expressed at compile time.\\n\\n- **Invariant Usefulness**: 8/10\\n  The validation in `WriteSession` (nil check, agent name mismatch, empty ref, empty data) prevents real bugs -- especially the agent name cross-check which prevents accidentally writing a Claude session via the Copilot agent. The pattern of returning `(nil, nil)` for pass-through hooks is documented with nolint comments and follows the established convention.\\n\\n- **Invariant Enforcement**: 7/10\\n  Construction-time enforcement is trivially satisfied (no state to validate). Runtime enforcement in `WriteSession` is thorough. `ReadSession` validates `SessionRef` but not `SessionID` (consistent with Claude Code). The `ExtractModelFromTranscript` function silently returns empty string on all errors, which is the correct design for a best-effort extraction.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n\\n1. **Strong consistency with existing agents.** The implementation follows the Claude Code agent pattern almost exactly: stateless struct, same method signatures, same validation logic in `ReadSession`/`WriteSession`, same chunking/reassembly delegation to shared helpers.\\n\\n2. **Compile-time interface compliance.** Both `HookSupport` and `TranscriptAnalyzer` are verified at compile time via nil-pointer assertions. The architecture test in `architecture_test.go` additionally enforces self-registration and import boundaries.\\n\\n3. **Robust hook file management.** The `InstallHooks`/`UninstallHooks` implementation uses raw `map[string]json.RawMessage` for round-tripping, which correctly preserves unknown fields and unknown hook types. This is a forward-compatible design that won't break when Copilot CLI adds new hook types.\\n\\n4. **Thorough test coverage.** Tests cover identity, session CRUD, transcript analysis, hook lifecycle, round-trip preservation, malformed input, idempotency, and force reinstall. The test quality is high.\\n\\n5. **Good separation of concerns.** Internal transcript parsing types (`copilotEvent`, `userMessageData`, `modelChangeData`, etc.) are unexported. The public API surface is minimal.\\n\\n### Concerns\\n\\n1. **`GetSupportedHooks` is dead code.** This method is defined on `CopilotCLIAgent` (hooks.go:267) but is not part of any interface and has zero callers in production code. It exists on OpenCode and Cursor agents too. It appears to be documentation-by-code, but it is not tested and will silently drift out of sync with `ParseHookEvent`. This is a codebase-wide issue, not specific to this PR.\\n\\n2. **`CopilotHooksFile.Version` has no validation.** The `InstallHooks` method defaults to `version: 1` on new files and preserves whatever exists on existing files, but there is no check that the version is actually 1. If Copilot CLI ships a v2 hooks format with breaking changes, this code will silently corrupt it.\\n\\n3. **`CopilotHookEntry.Type` is unconstrained.** The struct accepts any string for `Type`, but the install code always writes `\\\"command\\\"`. There is no validation that existing entries have a recognized type. This is fine for round-trip preservation but means the struct does not express its \\\"always command\\\" invariant.\\n\\n4. **Duplicate line-counting logic.** `GetTranscriptPosition` (lines 254-286 of transcript.go) and `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset` (lines 295-333) both implement JSONL line reading with `bufio.Reader`. This is identical to the Claude Code implementation. Both agents copy-paste the same `ReadBytes('\\\\n')` loop with EOF handling. The CLAUDE.md explicitly says to check for duplication.\\n\\n5. **`parseEventsFromOffset` loads everything into memory.** For `ExtractPrompts` and `ExtractSummary`, the entire transcript is read via `os.ReadFile` into memory, then all events are parsed into a `[]copilotEvent` slice. This is fine for current transcript sizes but is inconsistent with the streaming `bufio.Reader` approach used in `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset`.\\n\\n6. **`ReadSession` does not populate `ModifiedFiles`.** The Claude Code `ReadSession` parses the transcript and populates `session.ModifiedFiles`. The Copilot CLI `ReadSession` does not -- it returns `NativeData` but leaves `ModifiedFiles` empty. If any framework code relies on `ModifiedFiles` being populated after `ReadSession`, this will silently produce incomplete data. The Claude Code version calls `ExtractModifiedFiles(lines)` at line 133 of `claude.go`.\\n\\n### Recommended Improvements\\n\\n1. **Populate `ModifiedFiles` in `ReadSession`.** After reading the transcript bytes, parse events and extract modified files, mirroring what Claude Code does. This ensures the `AgentSession` contract is consistently fulfilled:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   events, _ := parseEventsFromBytes(data)\\n   return &agent.AgentSession{\\n       ...\\n       ModifiedFiles: extractModifiedFilesFromEvents(events),\\n   }, nil\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **Add a version check in `InstallHooks`.** Before modifying an existing hooks file, verify that `version` is 1. If it is not, return a clear error rather than potentially corrupting a v2 format. This is a low-cost guard.\\n\\n3. **Consider extracting the JSONL line-counting logic.** Both Claude Code and Copilot CLI implement identical `GetTranscriptPosition` and `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset` loop structures. A shared helper in the `agent` package (e.g.