ty and a `TranscriptPath` was provided:\\n\\n```go\\nmodel = ExtractModelFromTranscript(raw.TranscriptPath)\\nif model == \\\"\\\" {\\n    logging.Debug(ctx, \\\"copilot-cli: could not extract model from transcript\\\",\\n        \\\"transcriptPath\\\", raw.TranscriptPath)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nNote: `parseAgentStop` does not currently receive a `ctx` parameter either, which is a design gap that prevents any logging in this code path.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 2: `resolveTranscriptRef` returns empty string on error, propagating a broken state\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/lifecycle.go`, lines 143-152\\n\\n**Severity:** HIGH\\n\\n**Issue Description:** When `GetSessionDir` fails, this function logs a warning and returns `\\\"\\\"`. The caller `parseUserPromptSubmitted` (line 72) sets this empty string as `event.SessionRef`. Downstream in `lifecycle.go:278-280`, the TurnEnd handler checks for empty `SessionRef` and returns a hard error: `errors.New(\\\"transcript file not specified\\\")`. This means a failure to resolve the home directory during TurnStart will silently produce a broken session state, which then causes an unrelated-looking error at TurnEnd.\\n\\nThe warning log at line 148 says \\\"failed to resolve transcript path\\\" but does not include the `sessionID`, making it harder to correlate with the later TurnEnd failure.\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- `os.UserHomeDir()` failure (containerized environments, missing HOME)\\n- `ENTIRE_TEST_COPILOT_SESSION_DIR` set to an invalid path\\n\\n**User Impact:** Users in environments where `$HOME` is not set (containers, some CI systems) will see a confusing \\\"transcript file not specified\\\" error at turn end, with no clear connection to the actual root cause (home directory resolution failure at turn start).\\n\\n**Recommendation:** Either return an error from `resolveTranscriptRef` (changing the return type), or include the `sessionID` in the warning log so the failure can be correlated:\\n\\n```go\\nlogging.Warn(ctx, \\\"copilot-cli: failed to resolve transcript path\\\",\\n    \\\"sessionID\\\", sessionID, \\\"err\\\", err)\\n```\\n\\nThis is the same pattern as the cursor agent (cursor/lifecycle.go:69-70), so I acknowledge this is a pre-existing design choice, but the Copilot agent has a chance to do better.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 3: `parseEventsFromBytes` / `parseEventsFromOffset` silently skip malformed JSONL lines\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/transcript.go`, lines 97-98, and similar at line 315 in `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset`\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:** Malformed JSONL lines are silently skipped with `continue` and no logging. The doc comment says \\\"Malformed lines are silently skipped\\\" -- at least this is documented -- but it means that if Copilot CLI changes its JSONL format or if a file is corrupted, the code will silently produce incomplete results. Modified files will be missed, prompts will be lost, and model extraction will fail, all without any indication.\\n\\nThis pattern repeats in:\\n- `parseEventsFromOffset` (line 97-98)\\n- `extractModifiedFilesFromEvents` (line 118 and 128)\\n- `extractPromptsFromEvents` (line 146)\\n- `extractSummaryFromEvents` (line 161)\\n- `extractModelFromEvents` (lines 198, 215)\\n- `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset` (line 315)\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- Copilot CLI format changes that break our type definitions\\n- Partially written JSON (race condition with active session)\\n- Encoding issues\\n\\n**User Impact:** Silent data loss. Checkpoints may be missing files, prompts, or model information. The user has no way to know their data is incomplete.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** This is a design tradeoff (resilience vs. strictness for a streaming JSONL file), and skipping malformed lines is defensible for a file that may be actively written to. However, at minimum, consider counting skipped lines and logging a single summary warning if any were skipped:\\n\\n```go\\nskipped := 0\\n// ... in the loop:\\nif err := json.Unmarshal(line, &ev); err != nil {\\n    skipped++\\n    continue\\n}\\n// ... after the loop:\\nif skipped > 0 {\\n    // Return a warning count alongside events, or log if ctx is available\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 4: `InstallHooks` and `UninstallHooks` silently fall back to `\\\".\\\"` when worktree root resolution fails\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/hooks.go`, lines 49 and 168\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:** When `paths.WorktreeRoot(ctx)` fails, these functions fall back to `worktreeRoot = \\\".\\\"` without logging. If the CWD is not the repo root (e.g., the user is in a subdirectory, or in a container with a weird CWD), hooks will be installed to the wrong location -- `.github/hooks/entire.json` relative to the current directory instead of the repo root.\\n\\nI note this is the same pattern as the cursor agent (`cursor/hooks.go:62`), so this is a pre-existing issue being replicated. `AreHooksInstalled` at line 234 also does the same.\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- Not inside a git repository\\n- Git directory resolution failure\\n- Running from a subdirectory of the repo\\n\\n**User Impact:** Hooks silently installed in wrong directory. User thinks hooks are installed but they never fire. Debugging this would be extremely frustrating.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** At minimum, log a warning when falling back:\\n\\n```go\\nworktreeRoot, err := paths.WorktreeRoot(ctx)\\nif err != nil {\\n    logging.Warn(ctx, \\\"copilot-cli: could not resolve worktree root, falling back to cwd\\\", \\\"err\\\", err)\\n    worktreeRoot = \\\".\\\"\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 5: `ExtractModelFromTranscript` has no `context.Context` -- preventing all logging\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/transcript.go`, line 231; also `lifecycle.go` lines 95-113 (`parseAgentStop`)\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:** `ExtractModelFromTranscript` is a package-level function with no `context.Context` parameter. The project's logging infrastructure (`logging.Debug/Warn/Error`) requires a context. This means the function structurally cannot use the project's logging system, which explains why errors are silently swallowed.\\n\\nSimilarly, `parseAgentStop` (lifecycle.go:95) does not receive a `ctx` parameter, unlike `parseUserPromptSubmitted` which does. This prevents logging in the model extraction path.\\n\\n**User Impact:** Architectural gap that prevents proper observability for the core feature of this PR (model tracking).\\n\\n**Recommendation:** Add `ctx context.Context` as a parameter to `parseAgentStop` and pass it through to model extraction. Either make `ExtractModelFromTranscript` accept a context, or have the caller do the logging.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 6: `GetTranscriptPosition` returns 0 for empty path without error\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/transcript.go`, lines 254-256\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:** When `path` is empty, `GetTranscriptPosition` returns `(0, nil)` -- success with zero lines. This is the same return value as \\\"file exists but is empty.\\\" An empty path is likely a bug upstream (e.g., from the `resolveTranscriptRef` failure in Issue 2), and returning success here masks it. The caller `CapturePrePromptState` in `lifecycle.go` will store position=0, and everything downstream will proceed as if the transcript is empty.\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:** Propagated from Issue 2 -- an empty `SessionRef` from a failed transcript resolution flows through here undetected.\\n\\n**User Impact:** Pre-prompt state captures a position of 0 when it should have failed. Modified file detection will then process the entire transcript on every turn instead of just the delta, causing duplicate file entries in checkpoints.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** Return an error for empty path, or at minimum document that `(0, nil)` for empty path is intentional and expected (and why).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 7: `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset` returns nil for empty path without error\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/transcript.go`, lines 296-298\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:** Same pattern as Issue 6. Returns `(nil, 0, nil)` for empty path, which the caller interprets as \\\"no files modified, position 0\\\" -- indistinguishable from legitimate \\\"nothing happened.\\\"\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 8: E2E `StartSession` discards `s.SendKeys` errors\\n\\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/e2e/agents/copilot-cli.go`, line 129\\n\\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\\n\\n**Issue Description:** `_ = s.SendKeys(\\\"Enter\\\")` discards the error from sending keystrokes to the tmux session. If the tmux session has crashed or become unresponsive, this error is thrown away. The loop will continue trying to dismiss dialogs that no longer exist, eventually timing out on the next `WaitFor` with a confusing timeout error rather than the actual problem (tmux session gone).\\n\\n**Hidden Errors:**\\n- Tmux session crashed\\n- Tmux pane no longer exists\\n- Tmux server connection lost\\n\\n**User Impact:** E2E test failures will show \\\"waiting for startup prompt: timeout\\\" instead of the real error (tmux session died). This is in test infrastructure, but CLAUDE.md says \\\"tests should not be fixed by disabling them\\\" -- and bad error handling in test infra makes debugging flaky tests much harder.\\n\\n**Recommendation:**\\n```go\\nif err := s.SendKeys(\\\"Enter\\\"); err != nil {\\n    _ = s.Close()\\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to send Enter key to dismiss dialog: %w\\\", err)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 9: `ReadSession` uses `time.Now()` as `StartTime` instead of actu